ype":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bicarbonate","Digestive enzymes","Glucagon","Insulin","Somatostatin"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPancreatic acinar cells are specialised exocrine cells responsible for the \u003Cstrong\u003Eproduction of digestive enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E including trypsinogen, chymotrypsinogen, lipase and amylase. These enzymes are essential for the breakdown of proteins, fats, and carbohydrates in the small intestine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuctal cells, not acinar cells, are responsible for the \u003Cstrong\u003Eproduction of bicarbonate\u003C/strong\u003E. The endocrine cells of the pancreatic islets produce hormones: beta cells produce \u003Cstrong\u003Einsulin\u003C/strong\u003E, alpha cells produce \u003Cstrong\u003Eglucagon\u003C/strong\u003E, and delta cells produce \u003Cstrong\u003Esomatostatin\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcinar cells are arranged in grape-like clusters around small ducts, with abundant rough endoplasmic reticulum for protein synthesis and numerous secretory granules containing the inactive forms of digestive enzymes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pancreatic acinar cells produce and secrete digestive enzymes including trypsinogen, chymotrypsinogen, lipase, and amylase.","Pancreatic acinar cells are protein-producing cells arranged in grape-like clusters around small ducts."],"references":["Nightingale, J. M. (2012). Applied anatomy and physiology of the gastrointestinal tract (GIT). Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book: Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book, 45.","Podolsky, D. K., Camilleri, M., Fitz, J. G., Kalloo, A. N., Shanahan, F., \u0026 Wang, T. C. (Eds.). (2015). Yamada\u0027s textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abba